<dl id="n01048g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01048g">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01048g"> 48(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bought a paper to / see had he really / committed suicide (W) <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n01048g"><li>FW 99.33-100.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n01048g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n01048g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n01048g">MS BL 47471b-28</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:047 <a name="d20d" href="../../FF/fdra/dda.htm#d20d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/d20d.htm#n01048g">Draft: I.4&sect;2.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[WIFE&apos;S STORY IN NULLITY SUIT]</font> Further evidence was given in the petition for the nullity of marriage on the ground of the wife&apos;s refusal of marital relations presented by Mr. Samuel Herbert Hudston, aged 66, managing director of a Nottingham firm of wire-rope manufacturers, against his wife, Mrs. Lucy Ethel Hudston, who was formerly Mrs. Newbigging, of the Park Hotel, Preston <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Mrs. Hudston said that he <font color="green">[Mr. Hudston]</font> followed her to Windermere in October and repeated his proposal of marriage. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> She persisted in her refusal to marry him. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Turning to her he said &ldquo;My body will be found on the line at Sheffield to-night, and my death will be at your door.&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Mr. Hastings&mdash;<mark>Did you think he was going to commit suicide</mark> when he left you at Windermere?&mdash;Yes I really did. Did you make inquiries the next day?&mdash;Yes, I <mark>bought a paper to see if he had</mark>. (Laughter.) <small> <a name="DM25nov22" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DM25nov22"><cite title="source">Daily Mail</cite></a> (25 November 1922) 12/3-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A photograph of Mrs. Hudston appeared in the <cite>Daily Mail</cite> of 25 Nov 1922. </mm> </dd></dl>
